The main '''campus of [[University of the Philippines at Los Ba<U+00F1>os|University of the Philippines at Los Ba<U+00F1>os (UPLB)]]''' is located in the [[Municipalities of the Philippines|towns]] of [[Los Ba<U+00F1>os, Laguna|Los Ba<U+00F1>os]] and [[Bay, Laguna|Bay]] in the [[Provinces of the Philippines|province]] of [[Laguna province|Laguna]], some 64 kilometers southeast of [[Manila]]. It comprises of 5,445 hectares (13,450 acres) of land encompassing the entire [[Mount Makiling|Makiling Forest Reserve (MFR)]] and surrounding areas. Meanwhile, its [[land grant]]s, spread in the provinces of Laguna, [[Negros Occidental]] and [[Quezon]], have a combined land area of 9,760 hectares (24,120 acres). The land grants serve as UPLB's research sites and are mostly undeveloped.<ref name='OVCRE'>{{cite web|url = http://ovcre.uplb.edu.ph/index.php/about-uplb-rde/resources-for-research-extension/9-facilities-equipment-and-library-resources | title = Facilities, Equipment and Library Resources | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os Office of the Vice-Chancellor for Research and Extension | accessdate = 2011-04-11}}</ref>

The campus contains over 300 buildings,<ref name='UPLB Pride'>{{cite news|url = http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/202431/uplb-100-the-country-s-pride | author = Rachel C. Barawid | date = 2009-04-15 | accessdate = 2011-04-11 | newspaper = Manila Bulletin | title = UPLB at 100: The country<U+2019>s pride}}</ref> and equipment and facilities are estimated to be worth [[Philippine Peso|<U+20B1>]]10.6 billion (US$244 million)<ref name='conversion'>Approximate conversion value as of April 2011</ref> according to UPLB's [[financial statement]] for 2009.<ref name='COA'>{{cite book|title = Consolidated Annual Audit Report on the University of the Philippines |url = http://www.coa.gov.ph/2009_AAR/NGAs/Zipfiles/UP_aar09.zip | date = 2009-12-31| author = University of the Philippines | publisher = Commission on Audit | accessdate = 2011-04-11}}</ref> Additionally, it manages 8 student [[dormitory|dormitories]] inside the campus, which housed 2,170 of the 10,292 students enrolled in 2009.<ref name='A Statement on the Large Class Size Project'>{{cite book | url = http://uplb.edu.ph/email_attachments/2010-02-25_LargeClassStatement.pdf | title = A Statement on the Large Class Size Project | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os| accessdate = 2011-03-19}}</ref>

As of 2007, UPLB's 12 [[library|libraries]], collectively referred to as the University Library, hold a total of 346,061 [[volume (publishing)|volumes]]. The University Library is a periodic recipient of publications from the [[United Nations agencies]] (namely the [[UNFAO]], [[UN-HABITAT]] and [[United Nations University|UNU]]) and the [[World Bank]]. It is also a contributor to the [[AGRIS|International Information System for Agricultural Services and Technology]], to which it has contributed almost 30,000 titles between 1975 and 2010.<ref name='AGRIS'>{{cite web| url = http://agris.fao.org?query=%2B%28%20%2Bdate%3A%5B1965%20TO%202010%5D%20%2Bcenter%3A%28PH%29%20%2Bcenterkey%3A0%20%29&request_locale=en | title = Search AGRIS from 1975 to date | publisher = International Information System for Agricultural Services and Technology | accessdate = 2011-04-05}}</ref><ref name='mainlib'>{{cite web| url = http://mainlib.uplb.edu.ph/index.php/history | title = Brief History, Mission, and Vision | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os Main Library | date = 2009-03-11 | accessdate= 2011-04-06}}</ref>

==History==
{{see also|University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os#History|l1=History of University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os|University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os College of Agriculture#History|l2=History of UPLB College of Agriculture}}

The [[University of the Philippines|University of the Philippines (UP)]] [[Board of regents|Board of Regents]] initially purchased 72.63 hectares of abandoned farmland in 1909 at the foot of Mount Makiling to serve as the campus of the newly created UP College of Agriculture with students taking part in [[Deforestation|clearing]] the forest area. Classes were first held in tents while practical instruction were done at the [[plantation]]s, such as as [[corn]], [[sugar cane]] and [[tobacco]], in the campus. Expansion followed in February 1918 through [[list of Philippine laws|Act]] 2730 by the [[Philippine Legislature]], which appropriated 379 hectares for the creation of an "Agricultural Experiment Station," and <U+20B1>125,000 (US$2,900)<ref name="conversion"/> that was used by the college to further acquire 261.76 hectares of experimental farms and [[pasture|pasture land]].<ref name='CA history'>{{cite web|url = http://old.uplb.edu.ph/ca/aboutCA/ces/background | title = Historical Background | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os | accessdate = 2011-04-12}}</ref><ref name = '100 Years 0'>{{cite book| pages = 3<U+2013>46 | chapter = Chs. 1<U+2013>3 | chapterurl = http://www.slideshare.net/guest4f33786/100-years-chapters-13 | accessdate = 2011-04-11 | date = 2007 | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os Alumni Association, Inc. | location = Los Ba<U+00F1>os, Laguna | isbn = 978-971-547-252-4 | author = Fernando A. Bernardo |title = Centennial Panorama: Pictorial History of UPLB}}</ref>

Although most of the early structures had been demolished during the [[Japanese occupation of the Philippines]], some still exist up to this day, including the Palma Bridge and Baker Memorial Hall (both built during [[Dean (education)|Dean]] Bienvenido M. Gonzalez's term from 1927 to 1938). The [[Second World War|war]] destroyed 23 College of Agriculture buildings, 13 student [[dormitory|dormitories]] and [[bungalow]]s, 22 faculty and employee houses and all the student residences. The [[University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os College of Forestry and Natural Resources|School of Forestry]] was likewise devastated. Only the [[agricultural engineering]] building was left undamaged.<ref name = '100 Years'>{{cite book | pages = 75<U+2013>122 | chapter = Chs. 6<U+2013>8 | chapterurl = http://www.slideshare.net/frankahilario/100-years-chapters-68 | accessdate = 2011-04-11 | date = 2007 | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os Alumni Association, Inc. | location = Los Ba<U+00F1>os, Laguna | isbn = 978-971-547-252-4 | author = Fernando A. Bernardo |title = Centennial Panorama: Pictorial History of UPLB}}</ref>

Grants from [[USAID]] and Mutual Security Agency in the 1950s accelerated the development of the campus with the [[University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os Graduate School|Graduate School]] building, the UPCA Library (now [[University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os College of Arts and Sciences|College of Arts and Sciences]] building) and the Women's Dormitory (now Math Building) built during this period. Meanwhile, grants from the [[United States|US]] Economic Cooperation Agency worth US$239,552, the International Cooperation Administration (ICA) worth US$175,000, and ICA-[[United States National Economic Council|National Economic Council]] allowed the construction of the Forest Products Laboratory (believed to to the "largest and best equipped in the [[eastern hemisphere]]" by the time it was constructed) in 1954<ref name='DOST Forest'>{{cite web|url = http://fprdi.dost.gov.ph/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=42&Itemid=67 | title = History | date = 2007-07-01 | accessdate = 2011-04-13 | publisher = Forest Products Research and Development Institute }}</ref>, the Agricultural Credit and Cooperatives Institute in 1957, and further construction of school and dormitory buildings in the School of Forestry campus in the 1960s, respectively.<ref name="100 Years"/><ref name = '100 Years 2'>{{cite book| pages = 123<U+2013>160 | chapter = Chs. 9<U+2013>10 | chapterurl = http://www.slideshare.net/frankahilario/100-years-chapters-910 | accessdate = 2011-04-11 | date = 2007 | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os Alumni Association, Inc. | location = Los Ba<U+00F1>os, Laguna | isbn = 978-971-547-252-4 | author = Fernando A. Bernardo |title = Centennial Panorama: Pictorial History of UPLB}}</ref>

[[File:1-2ps 00238.jpg.jpg|thumb|left|In February 1962, [[Ford Foundation]] funded US$6.9 million for the construction of the [[International Rice Research Institute]].<ref name="100 Years 2"/>]]

Aside from international assistance, Five-Year Development Programs in during the terms of [[Dean (education)|Dean]] Domingo Lantican (1958-1971) of the School of Forestry, and Dean [[Dioscoro Umali]] (1959-1970) of the College of Agriculture were also instrumental in developing the campus. Pavement of roads and construction of several buildings, such as the administration buildings of the College of Agriculture and the College of Development Communications, and staff houses, were built during the programs.<ref name="100 Years 2"/>

Since 2008, efforts have been put into renovation and beautification of existing structures, including pavement of path walks and construction of lampposts (of which there have been 119 installed as of January 2009),<ref name='Lamppost'>{{cite journal | url = http://www.scribd.com/doc/11645011/uplb-perspective-0809-7th-ish | page = 6 | title = Admin steps up UPLB ecotourism projects | author = Faith Allyson Buenacasa et al | journal = UPLB Perspective | volume = 35 | issue = 7 | date = 2009-01-29 | accessdate = 2011-04-15}}</ref> as part of UPLB's plans to repair damages from a [[Typhoon Xangsane|2006 typhoon]], and to promote the campus as a "walking museum" and an [[ecotourism]] center to raise income. Likewise, construction of an 11,000-[[seating capacity|seater]] [[convention center]] and [[cable car]]s connecting the lower and upper campuses have been proposed in line with the ecotourism promotion in cooperation with private entities.<ref name = 'ecotourism'>{{cite journal | title = Science meets Culture meets Nature: UPLB envisions Mariang Makiling Eco-Tourism Village | publisher = University of the Philippines | journal = UP Newsletter |  location = Quezon City | volume = 32 | issue = 3 | author = Celeste Ann Castillo Llaneta | date = March 2011 | accesdate = 2011-04-15 | url = http://www.up.edu.ph/upnewsletter2.php?i=890&pg=905&pgidx=&pgmax=1&issue=75}}</ref> Portions of the student body, however, criticized the program, arguing that the funds could have been better allocated to renovation of classrooms, laboratories and other academic facilities.<ref name='misallocation'>{{cite journal | url = http://fc02.deviantart.net/fs38/f/2008/353/4/e/5th_Issue_by_uplbperspective0809.pdf | title = UPLB admin steps up beautification campaign | author = Katrina Elauria | journal = UPLB Perspective | date = 2008-12-17 | volume= 35 | issue = 5 | accessdate = 2011-04-15 | page = 2}}</ref>

A [[memorandum]] issued by [[Chancellor]] Luis Rey I. Velasco in 2010 instructs UPLB to [[energy conservation|conserve energy]] in hopes of reducing operating costs. Minimizing the use of [[electric appliances]] (such as [[air conditioner]]s, [[electric stove]]s and [[oven]]s), [[car pooling]] and [[recycling]] has been advised.<ref name='Velasco'>{{cite web | url = http://www.uplb.edu.ph/index.php/news/334-clriv-reminds-constituents-to-conserve-energy | title = CLRIV reminds constituents to conserve energy | author = Office of the Chancellor | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os | date = 2010-10-13 | accessdate = 2011-04-24}}</ref>
{{clear}}

==Areas==
