{{wide image|UPLB Campus map.png|1000px}}
{{hidden end}}
[[File:Tanghalang Maria Makiling.jpg|left|thumb|Tanghalang Maria Makiling at the National Arts Center]]
===Upper campus===

The College of Forestry and Natural Resources, [[University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os College of Public Affairs|College of Public Affairs]], [[National Arts Center]],<ref name='NAC'>{{cite web | url = http://www.culturalcenter.gov.ph/page.php?page_id=131 | title = National Arts Center | publisher = Cultural Center of the Philippines | accessdate = 2011-04-16}}</ref> [[Philippine High School for the Arts]],<ref name = 'PHSA'>{{cite web| url = http://www.phsa.edu.ph/home.htm | title = Official website | publisher = Philippine High School of the Arts | accessdate = 2011-04-16}}</ref> the site of the [[Jamboree (Scouting)|National Jamboree]] of the [[Boy Scouts of the Philippines]],<ref name='Jamboree'>{{cite news| url = http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view/20071023-96321/17%2C000_boy_scouts_start_Jamboree_in_Mt._Makiling | title = 17,000 boy scouts start Jamboree in Mt. Makiling | newspaper = Manila Bulletin | author = Ni<U+00F1>a Catherine Calleja | date = 2007-10-23 | accessdate = 2011-04-16}}</ref> are on the upper campus, which is located on Mount Makiling. The upper campus includes the entire 4,347-hectare<ref name='OVCRE'>{{cite web| url = http://ovcre.uplb.edu.ph/index.php/about-uplb-rde/resources-for-research-extension/9-facilities-equipment-and-library-resources | title = Facilities, Equipment and Library Resources | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os Office of the Vice-Chancellor for Research and Extension | accessdate = 2011-04-16}}</ref> Makiling Forest Reserve. It is also the site of the Center for Philippine Raptors<ref name='OAR'>{{cite web | url = http://up.edu.ph/~oarmain/?page_id=675&page=3 | title = UP Los Ba<U+00F1>os | publisher= University of the Philippines Office of Alumni Relations | accessdate = 2011-04-16}}</ref> and the [[Bureau of Plant Industry (Philippines)|Bureau of Plant Industry]]-Makiling Botanic Gardens, one of the oldest parts of the campus. The location of the gardens used to be the place where the tents, which were used as classrooms during the first four months of the university, were set up.<ref name="100 Years 0"/>

The MFR serves a an outdoor laboratory to students, mostly from the College of Forestry and Natural Resources. Jurisdiction of the MFR, both created in 1910, was originally under the Bureau of Forestry. It was only in 1960 when administration of the MFR was transferred to UP. [[National Power Corporation|NAPOCOR]] acquired complete jurisdiction of the MFR, however, in 1987 as part of the [[Philippines]]' [[energy development]] program under [[President of the Philippines|President]] [[Corazon Aquino]]. The MFR was returned to UPLB three years later by effect of [[Republic Act|RA]] 6967.<ref name='RA 6967'>{{cite web|url = http://www.lawphil.net/statutes/repacts/ra1990/ra_6967_1990.html | title = Republic Act No. 6967 | author = Congress of the Philippines | publisher = Lawphil.net | date = 1990-10-15 | accessdate= 2011-04-16}}</ref><ref name='MFR'>{{cite web| url = http://pcarrd.dost.gov.ph/cin/watershed/gis/BAAA/bodyBAAA.htm | title = Makiling Forest Reserve (MFR) | publisher = Philippine Council for Agriculture, Forestry and Natural Resources Research and Development | accessdate = 2011-04-16}}</ref> In 2008, [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Representative]] Del De Guzman of the [[Legislative districts of Makati City|2<sup>nd</sup> district of Makati]] filed  HB 1143, which, if passed into law, would have transfered jurisdiction of the MFR to the Boy Scouts of the Philippines. The [[bill (proposed law)|bill]] was strongly opposed by UPLB, citing possible mismanagement and deforestation of the site if placed under the BSP, among others.<ref name='Jamboree 1'>{{cite news| url = http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/192952/plans-put-mt-makiling-under-boy-scouts-opposed | date = 2008-11-21 | author = Ferdinand Castro | title = Plans to put Mt. Makiling under Boy Scouts opposed | newspaper = Manila Bulletin | accessdate = 2011-04-16}}</ref><ref name='Jamboree 2'>{{cite journal | url = http://www.up.edu.ph/upnewsletter.php?issue=47&i=767 | title = UPLB says no to House Bill 1143 | author = Bernice P. Varona | date = 2008-11-01 | volume = 29  | issue = 11 | journal = UP Newsletter |  location = Quezon City | accessdate = 2011-04-16 | publisher = University of the Philippines}}</ref><ref name='Jamboree 3'>{{cite web | url = http://old.uplb.edu.ph/announce/1326 | title = UPLB says NO to House Bill 1143 and the fragmentation of the Mt. Makiling Forest Reserve | date = 2008-11-10 | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os | accessdate = 2011-04-16}}</ref><ref name='Jamboree 4'>{{cite journal | url = http://www.scribd.com/doc/11644791/uplb-perspective-0809-4th-ish | title = BSP eyes control of Jamboree | author = Nikko Angelo Oribiana | journal = UPLB Perspective | date = 2008-12-15 | volume = 35 | issue = 4 | page = 3 | accessdate = 2011-04-16}}</ref>

===Lower campus===
[[File:SEARCA.jpg|SEARCA|thumb|right]]

The 1,098-hectare<ref name="OVCRE"/> lower campus, located at foot of Mt. Makiling, is the location of most UPLB units and affiliated entities, including the International Rice Research Institute,<ref name='IRRI'>{{cite web|url = http://irri.org/about-irri/contact-us | title = Contact Us | publisher = International Rice Research Institute | accessdate = 2011-03-27}}</ref> [[ASEAN Center for Biodiversity]],<ref name ='ACB'>{{cite web | url = http://www.aseanbiodiversity.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=72&Itemid=86 | title = Contact Us | publisher = ASEAN Center for Biodiversity| accessdate = 2011-03-19}}</ref> [[World Agroforestry Centre]]<ref name= 'Agroforestry'>{{cite web | url = http://www.worldagroforestry.org/sea/apps/staffdirectory/DisplayStaff2.asp?GrupID=F,FPLB | title = Site Based Los Banos (Philippines)| publisher = World Agroforestry Centre | accessdate = 2011-03-19}}</ref> and the [[Southeast Asian Regional Center for Graduate Study and Research in Agriculture|Southeast Asian Regional Center for Graduate Study and Research in Agriculture (SEARCA)]].<ref name= 'SEARCA'>{{cite web | url = http://beta.searca.org/searca/index.php/about-us/contact-us | title = Contact Us | publisher = Southeast Asian Regional Center for Graduate Study and Research in Agriculture | accessdate = 2011-03-27}}</ref>

The [[Molawin River]], a tributary of [[Laguna de Bay]], runs through the campus. Several bridges, such as the Palma Bridge (named after [[President of the University of the Philippines|President]] Rafael V. Palma), cross through the river. A 1996 UPLB study found high concentrations of [[nitrate]]s and [[phosphate]]s in the river, believed to be from decaying garbage and [[domestic waste]].<ref name='Millennium'>{{cite book| url = http://www.maweb.org/documents_sga/Philippine%20SGA%20Report.pdf | title = Ecosystem and People: The Philippine Millennium Ecosystem Assessment (MA) Sub-global Assessment | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os College of Forestry and Natural Resources | editor = Rodel D. Lasco | editor2 = Ma. Victoria O. Espaldon | date = 2005 | isbn = 971-547-237-0 | author = Ma. Victoria O. Espaldon et al | accessdate = 2011-04-16}}</ref> There have been recent efforts in rehabilitating the river, such as planting ''[[species:Mussaenda|Mussaenda]]'' and ''[[Hibiscus]]'' on its [[bank (geography)|bank]].<ref name='drugstore'>{{cite web| url = http://www.uplb.edu.ph/index.php/news/312-university-teams-up-with-senior-citizens-drugstore-to-help-restore-molawin-creek | title = University teams up with senior citizens and drugstore to help restore Molawin Creek | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os | date = 2010-08-12 | accessdate = 2011-04-16}}</ref><ref name='balita'>{{cite web|url = http://balita.ph/2010/11/06/uplb-botanist-wants-science-brought-to-laguna-lake-riverside-communities/ | publisher = Balita.ph | title = UPLB botanist wants science brought to Laguna Lake, riverside communities | date = 2010-11-06 | agency = Philippine News Agency | accessdate = 2011-04-16}}</ref>

===Land grants===

UPLB has three major [[land grant]]s: the Laguna-Quezon Land Grant, La Carlota Land Grant and Laguna Land Grant.<ref name="OVCRE"/>

The 5,719-hectare Laguna-Quezon Land Grant is located in the towns of [[Real, Quezon]] and [[Siniloan, Laguna]] and was acquired in February 1930. It covers some portions of the [[Sierra Madre (Philippines)|Sierra Madre]] mountain range, and currently hosts the university<U+2019>s ''[[Citronella (genus)|Citronella]]'' and [[lemongrass]] [[plantations]].<ref name='Citronella'>{{cite web | url = http://lgmo.uplb.edu.ph/index.php/pr/ceop | title = Citronella Essential Oil Production at the Laguna-Quezon Land Grant | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os Land Grant Management Office | accessdate = 2011-03-27 | date = 2010-09-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://lgmo.uplb.edu.ph/index.php/about | title = History | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os Land Grant Management Office | accessdate = 2010-10-18}}</ref> The 705-hectare [[Negros Occidental|La Carlota]] Land Grant is situated in Negros Occidental, a province in the Western Visayas region. Acquired in May 1964, it houses the [[Department of Science and Technology (Philippines)|PCARRD-DOST]] La Granja Agricultural Research Center<ref name= 'Research consortium'>{{cite news | url = http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=96813 | title = Research consortium for ARMM pushed | author = Rudy A. Fernandez | date = 2001-01-01 | newspaper = The Philippine Star | accessdate = 2011-03-27}}</ref> which serves as a research center for various upland crops.<ref name="OVCRE"/><ref name = 'Accomplishments'>{{cite web | url = http://old.uplb.edu.ph/ca/lagranja/accomp | title = Accomplishments | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os | accessdate = 2011-03-27}}</ref> Meanwhile, the 3,336-hectare<ref name="OVCRE"/> Laguna Land Grant, located in [[Paete, Laguna]], is mostly undeveloped.<ref name = "Brief History"/>

Numerous parties have expressed interest in developing the land grants; however, UPLB has not entertained the potential investors due to the "lack of a solid development plan."<ref name = 'Brief History'>{{cite web | url = http://lgmo.uplb.edu.ph/index.php/about/history | title = Brief History | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os Land Grant Management Office | accessdate = 2011-03-27 | date = 2010-12-03}}</ref>

==Buildings and landmarks==
[[File:The Pegaraw and the UPLB Main Library.jpg|right|200px|thumb|The Main Library behind the ''Philippine Pegasus'']]
[[File:Uplb carillon.jpg|right|thumb|180px|The Rizal Centenary Carillon]]
Majority of the current buildings at UPLB were built between 1965 to 1975. Prior to this, most buildings were made of [[hardwood]].<ref name='Devcom'>{{cite book| url = http://www.upou.edu.ph/papers/flibrero_2009/DevcomLB_history.pdf | title = Development Communication Los Ba<U+00F1>os Style: A Story Behind the History | publisher = University of the Philippines Open University | author = Lex Librero | date = 2008 | pages = 3<U+2013>4 | accessdate = 2011-04-18}}</ref>

Many of the more prominent buildings in the campus were designed by [[National Artists of the Philippines|National Artist]] for [[Architecture]] [[Leandro Locsin]], who is known for his [[brutalism|extensive use of concrete]] and simplistic design.<ref name='NCCA'>{{cite web|url = http://www.ncca.gov.ph/about-ncca/org-awards/architecture/leandro_locsin.php | title = Leandro V. Locsin | publisher = National Commission for Culture and the Arts | accessdate = 2011-04-16}}</ref> The buildings in the campus, which he designed, include:<ref name='Arkitektura'>{{cite web | url = http://www.arkitektura.ph/?p=architects&view=1 | title = Leandro V. Locsin | accessdate = 2011-03-27 | publisher = Arkitekturang Filipino}}</ref>
*'''Dioscoro L. Umali Hall''', an [[auditorium]] named after Dean [[Dioscoro L. Umali]] built during his US$6-million and <U+20B1>23-million (US$532,000)<ref name="conversion"/> Five-Year Development Program implemented in 1965.<ref name = '100 Years 2'>{{cite book| pages = 123<U+2013>160 | chapter = Chs. 9<U+2013>10 | chapterurl = http://www.slideshare.net/frankahilario/100-years-chapters-910 | accessdate = 2011-03-20 | date = 2007 | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os Alumni Association, Inc. | location = Los Ba<U+00F1>os, Laguna | isbn = 978-971-547-252-4 | author = Fernando A. Bernardo |title = Centennial Panorama: Pictorial History of UPLB}}</ref><ref name = '100 Years 3'>{{cite book| pages = 161<U+2013>186 | chapter = Chs. 11<U+2013>12 | chapterurl = http://www.slideshare.net/frankahilario/100-years-chapters-1112 | accessdate = 2011-03-20 | date = 2007 | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os Alumni Association, Inc. | location = Los Ba<U+00F1>os, Laguna | isbn = 978-971-547-252-4 | author = Fernando A. Bernardo |title = Centennial Panorama: Pictorial History of UPLB}}</ref> Arkitekturang Filipino, a colaboration of the [[National Commission for Culture and the Arts]] and the [[United Architects of the Philippines]], calls it a "clear example of his distinct architecture", and identifies its resemblance with the Nicanor Abelardo Hall at the [[Cultural Center of the Philippines]].<ref name="Arkitektura"/> It also houses the Sining Makiling Gallery, an [[art gallery]].<ref name="OAR"/>
*'''Main Library''', which has a total floor area of 6,336 m<sup>2</sup> and a [[seating capacity]] of 510 making it the largest [[library]] in UPLB. It holds 195,282 [[volume (publishing)|volume]]s, [[theses]], digital sources and 1,215 [[serial publication|serial titles]], among others.<ref name="OVCRE"/> SEARCA originally had it built as its library in 1974. It was eventually transferred to the university as the successor of the University of the Philippines College of Agriculture Library.<ref name='mainlib'>{{cite web| url = http://mainlib.uplb.edu.ph/index.php/history | title = Brief History, Mission, and Vision | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os Main Library | date = 2009-03-11 | accessdate= 2011-04-16}}</ref><ref name = '100 Years 3'>{{cite book| pages = 161<U+2013>186 | chapter = Chs. 11<U+2013>12 | chapterurl = http://www.slideshare.net/frankahilario/100-years-chapters-1112 | accessdate = 2011-04-17 | date = 2007 | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os Alumni Association, Inc. | location = Los Ba<U+00F1>os, Laguna | isbn = 978-971-547-252-4 | author = Fernando A. Bernardo |title = Centennial Panorama: Pictorial History of UPLB}}</ref> It is believed to be the largest [[agriculture|agricultural]] library in [[Asia]].<ref name='Get lost'>{{cite journal| url = http://www.scribd.com/doc/11644612/uplb-perspective-0809-1st-ish?query=leandro | title = How (not) to get lost in UPLB | author = Karen Lapitan | journal = UPLB Perspective | volume= 35 | issue = 1 | date = 2008-08-01 | accessdate = 2011-04-21 }}</ref>
*'''Rizal Centennary Carillon''', built in 1996 and named after [[National hero of the Philippines|Philippine National Hero]] [[Jos<U+00E9> Rizal]]. It has 37 [[Bell (instrument)|bells]] ranging from [[F (musical note)|F]] 3 [[octave]]s below [[middle C]] up to [[G (musical note)|G]] above middle C,<ref name='IRRI guide'>{{cite book| url = http://books.google.com.ph/books?id=4Q61gK9IfIkC&lpg=PA16&ots=Zq5tMsysiU&dq=rizal%20centenary%20carillon&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q=rizal%20centenary%20carillon&f=false | title = A guide to Los Ba<U+00F1>os for IRRI international staff & families | author = Kate Kirk | author2 = Katherine Lopez | publisher = International Rice Research Institute | date = 2001 | isbn = 9712201600 | accessdate = 2011-04-17}}</ref><ref name='Carillon 1'>{{cite web|url = http://www.gcna.org/data/PHLBNSUP.HTM | title = Rizal Centenary Carillon | date = 2008-08-24 | accessdate = 2011-04-17 | publisher = Guild of Carilloneurs in North America }}</ref> making it the second largest [[List of carillons#Non-traditional carillons|non-traditional carillon]] in the [[Asia-Pacific]] in terms of number of bells. It is also one of the only two non-traditional carillons in the Philippines.<ref name='Carillon'>{{cite web | url = http://www.gcna.org/data/IXAPNTnr.html | title = Non-traditional carillons in Asia and the Pacific Rim: index by size | publisher = Guild of Carilloneurs in North America | accessdate=2011-04-17 | date = 2010-01-20}}</ref>
*'''Student Union''', which houses the offices of the Office of Student Affairs, University Food Service,<ref name='OSA'>{{cite web|url = http://old.uplb.edu.ph/osa/253 | title = Basic Student Information | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os | accessdate = 2011-04-18}}</ref> University Student Council and ''UPLB Perspective'' (the official [[student newspaper|student publication]] of UPLB).<ref name='Get lost'>{{cite journal| url = http://www.scribd.com/doc/11644612/uplb-perspective-0809-1st-ish?query=leandro | title = How (not) to get lost in UPLB | author = Karen Lapitan | journal = UPLB Perspective | volume= 35 | issue = 1 | date = 2008-08-01 | accessdate = 2011-04-21 | language = Tagalog}}</ref>
Other structures that were built by National Artists include:
*[[replica]] of the '''''[[Oblation (University of the Philippines)|Oblation]]''''' by [[Napoleon Abueva]]. The original is a 3.5-meter [[statue]] by [[Guillermo Tolentino]], Abueva's [[mentor]], commissioned in 1935 by UP President [[Rafael Palma]]. The sculpture is based on the second stanza of Rizal's ''[[Mi <U+00FA>ltimo adi<U+00F3>s]]'' ([[Spanish language|Spanish]] for ''My last farewell''). A replica of the ''Oblation'' can be found on each of the major UP campuses, and has since become the campuses' identifying landmark.<ref name='UP Oblation'>{{cite web| url = http://upaagc.org/oblation.html | title = U.P. Oblation History | publisher = University of the Philippines Alumni Association of Greater Chicago | accessdate = 2011-04-21}}</ref><ref name='Abueva'>{{cite web| url = http://oblation.com.ph/artist.htm | title = Napoleon V. Abueva, the National Artist | publisher = Oblation.com.ph | accessdate = 2011-04-21}}</ref>
*'''''Philippine Pegasus''''' (also referred to as the '''''Pegaraw'''''), a winged [[tamaraw]] sculpted by Abueva.<ref name='Pegaraw'>{{cite web|url = http://www.uplb.edu.ph/index.php/news/342-portals-landmarks-turned-over-to-uplb-new-marker-unveiled | title = Portals, landmarks turned over to UPLB; new marker unveiled | author = Jennielyn R. Carpio | author2=  JG Garcia | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os | date = 2010-11-03 | accessdate = 2011-04-21}}</ref><ref name="OAR"/>

==Transportation and amenities==

[[Public transportation|Public utility]] [[jeepney]]s are a popular means of transportation around the campus. Since August 2007, a new jeepney route has been under implementation. Jeepney drivers have been since required to post ''kanan'' ([[Tagalog language|Tagalog]] for "right") or ''kaliwa'' ("left"), in reference to their direction. The new route prohibits access to the "middle campus," which contains most of the university's main buildings, to promote walking, and lessen noise and air pollution inside the campus. Being the riding point of many passengers, jeepney drivers calculate a loss of <U+20B1>200-300 (US$5-7)<ref name="conversion"/> and 90% loss of passengers. Due to this, the implementation was met with protest, including a [[Strike action|transport strike]]. Similarly, a [[walkout]] was staged by around 500 students, with students speculating alleged lack of community consultation before its implementation.<ref name='USC letter'>{{Cite web | url = http://www.arkibongbayan.org/2008-02Feb29-UP/doc/uplb%20supports%20transport%20strike.txt | title = Drivers paralyze transport in UPLB; students support transport strike amid continuing protests for GMA ouster | author = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os University Student Council | publisher = Arkibong Bayan | date = 2009-02-26 | accessdate = 2011-04-24}}</ref><ref name = 'transpo2'>{{cite journal | url = http://fc01.deviantart.com/fs19/f/2007/270/e/d/UPLB_Perspective_Vol_34_Issue1_by_uplbperspective0708.pdf | title = OVCCA rejects USC, LBCTF appeals: PUJ rerouting <U+2018>dry run<U+2019> continues | author = Rogene Gonzales | page = 10 | journal = UPLB Perspective | volume = 34 | issue = 1 | date = 2007-09-27 | accessdate = 2011-04-24}}</ref> The [[mayor]] of [[Los Ba<U+00F1>os, Laguna|Los Ba<U+00F1>os]] refused to interfere.<ref name='transpo'>{{cite journal | url = http://fc02.deviantart.com/fs20/f/2007/296/5/2/UPLB_Perspective_Vol_34_Issue2_by_uplbperspective0708.pdf | title = Velasco firm on ambulant vending, rerouting issues | author = Angelica Mendoza | author2 = Harriet Melanie Zabala | date = 2007-10-22 | volume= 34 | issue = 2 | journal = UPLB Perspective | accessdate = 2011-04-24 | page = 2}}</ref>

Numerous [[local church|congregations]] can be found near UPLB. These include the [[United Church of Christ in the Philippines|UCCP]] Church Among the Palms,<ref name='UCCP-CAP'>{{cite web|url = http://www.cap-uccp.com/ | title = Official website | publisher = UCCP Church Among the Palms | accessdate =2011-04-09}}</ref> the [[Parish (Catholic Church)|Catholic parish]]es of [[St. Therese of the Child Jesus]]<ref name='mass sched'>{{cite web|url = http://www.mass-schedules.com/catholic-church/780/st-therese-of-the-child-jesus-parish.html | title= Catholic Mass Schedule at St. Therese of the Child Jesus Parish | publisher = Philippine Catholic Mass Schedule | accessdate = 2011-04-09}}</ref> and [[Anthony of Padua|San Antonio de Padua]],<ref name='Sn Antonio'>{{cite web | url = http://home.catholicweb.com/sadpplbs/ | title = Official website | publisher = San Antonio de Padua Parish, Los Ba<U+00F1>os, Laguna | accessdate=2011-04-09}}</ref> and [[Victory Christian Fellowship|Victory Los Ba<U+00F1>os]].<ref name='Victory'>{{cite web| url = http://www.victory.org.ph/assets/docs/churches/southern-luzon/los-banos.pdf | title = Victory Los Ba<U+00F1>os | date = 2010-09-09 | publisher = Victory Christian Fellowship | accessdate = 2011-04-09}}</ref> Other [[amenity|amenities]] include [[bank]]s (including [[Land Bank of the Philippines|LBP]],<ref name='LBP'>{{Cite web| url = http://www.landbank.com/branch.asp | title = Branch locator | publisher = Land Bank of the Philippines | accessdate = 2011-04-09}}</ref> [[Plantersbank]]<ref name = 'Plantersbank'>{{cite web| url = http://www.plantersbank.com.ph/branches/ | title = Branches | publisher = Planters Development Bank | accessdate = 2011-04-09}}</ref> and [[Philippine National Bank|PNB]])<ref name='PNB'>{{cite web| url = http://www.pnb.com.ph/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=224&Itemid=206 | title = Luzon Branches | publisher = Philippine National Bank | accessdate = 2011-04-09}}</ref> and [[mall]]s, such as [[Robinsons Malls|Robinsons Town Mall Los Ba<U+00F1>os]].<ref name='Robinson'>{{cite web|url = http://www.robinsonsmalls.com/malls_losbanos.php | title = Robinsons Town Mall Los Ba<U+00F1>os | publisher = Robinsons Malls | accessdate = 2011-04-09}}</ref> [[Security]] is provided by the University Police Force<ref name='UPF'>{{cite web| url = http://upf.uplb.edu.ph/index.php?option=com_content&view=frontpage&Itemid=55 | title = UPLB University Police Force | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os | date = 2010-09-15 | accessdate = 2011-04-09}}</ref> and the Community Support Brigade<ref name='CSB'>{{cite web| url = http://ovcca.uplb.edu.ph/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=59&Itemid=64 | title = Community Support Brigade | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os Office of the Vice-Chancellor for Community Affairs | accessdate = 2011-04-09 | author = Eduardo A. Panaya }}</ref> in addition to the [[police]] force of the [[local government]]. Meanwhile, [[medical services]] are provided by the University Health Service, a 30-bed [[hospital]] with specialized facilities, such as a [[diabetes]] [[clinic]] and a [[neonatal intensive-care unit]], in addition to its [[emergency room|emergency]] and [[operating room]]s, among others.<ref name='UHS'>{{cite web| url = http://old.uplb.edu.ph/ovcca/211 | title = Facilities/Services/Programs | publisher = University of the Philippines Los Ba<U+00F1>os | accessdate = 2011-04-25}}</ref>

